The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Telegraph meet begins today
                                                                                                                       7                                      Telegraph meet begins today
            A STAFF REPORTER                      
	Calcutta: The 22nd The Telegraph Schools Chess Championship, in association with Alekhine Chess Club and presented by Himani Sona Chandi Chyawanprash, begins at Gorky Sadan, here on Saturday.         
	Sayantan Das will defend the title in the tournament  the only schoool-level Fide rating schools meet in the country  to be inaugurated by Grandmaster and a product of The Telegraph Schools chess meet, Surya Sekhar Ganguly.         
	Diptayan Ghosh, Prince Bajaj, Khushi Dharewa, Mitrabha Guha and Sidhanth Mohapatra are some of the prominent names who will be seen in action during the nine-day meet.         
	Four-year-olds Hrishiraj Chowdhury and Ritiwika Ghosh will be the youngest boy and girl participating at this years meet.         
	The total prize money is Rs 1,20,000 with the winner taking home Rs 21,000 and a trophy.         
	There will also be age-group prizes. In the boys section, the first to the sixth will get prizes, while in the girls section, the first to fourth will get mementoes.         
	Around 480 students from 160 schools will be participating in the tournament to be played in 11 round Swiss League format. This is also the highest number of participants the tournament has seen.         
	Besides Bengal, the meet will see participants from the states of Bihar, Uttar Pradesh, Delhi, Mizoram, Assam, Andhra Pradesh, Jharkhand, Orissa and Tamil Nadu.         
	There are 10 overseas participants with six from Bangladesh and four from Nepal. The Bangladesh contingent, however, are yet to reach the city because of visa problems. If they land in city on Saturday, they will be given, like last year, first round byes.                                                                                                                     
